weather-scenarios.live-data-desc: Fetch live weather data for your nearest airport from noaa.gov. You need a working internet connection. Weather is generated automatically, once a valid METAR is received.
weather-scenarios.manual-input-desc: Enter your favorite METAR weather. A valid METAR syntax is required.
weather-scenarios.core-high-pressure-region-desc: The center of a high pressure region, characterized by descending air and hence only weak cloud development with high visibility.
weather-scenarios.high-pressure-region-desc: A high pressure region, characterized by moderate to strong Cumulus development in the afternoon and fairly good visibility conditions.
weather-scenarios.border-high-pressure-region-name: Border of a high pressure region
weather-scenarios.border-high-pressure-region-desc: The border of a high pressure region, in which the airmass becomes unstable and various convective and stratiform clouds may appear.
weather-scenarios.border-low-pressure-region-name: Border of a low pressure region
weather-scenarios.border-low-pressure-region-desc: The border of a low pressure region, in which the airmass is unstable and convective clouds start to form layers and merge into stratiform clouds.
weather-scenarios.low-pressure-region-desc: A low pressure region, characterized by rising air, widespread formation of stratiform clouds and beginning rain.
weather-scenarios.core-low-pressure-region-desc: The core of a low pressure region, characterized by overcast clouds, bad visibility on the ground and significant rainfall.
weather-scenarios.warm-sector-desc: A warm sector, characterized by high moisture in the air and haze extending up to high altitudes, but otherwise largely convective cloud development.
weather-scenarios.fair-weather-desc: A lovely day for trip to your favorite 100$ hamburger airfield
weather-scenarios.thunderstorm-desc: A hot and damp summer day with thunderstorms developing in the afternoon. Be prepared for reduction of visibility in showers and strong gusts near thunderstorms
weather-scenarios.stormy-monday-desc: You're out for an adventure? Gusty winds blowing from the west and isolated thunderstorms should be avoided. Fasten your seatbelt!
weather-scenarios.marginal-vfr-desc: After the storm - limited visibility and some showers. Go or No-Go?
weather-scenarios.cat-one-minimum-desc: If you just got your IFR rating, this is what you are allowed to do. But can you?
weather-scenarios.cat-two-minimum-desc: With just a 1/4 mile visibility and clouds at 100ft, you don't see much of the runway until seconds before touchdown. Trust your instruments to stay alive.
weather-scenarios.cat-three-b-minimum-desc: This is expert level. You will barely see the taxiway from the cockpit, even if you are on ground. Fog and light drizzle, freezing level at 1000ft.
weather-scenarios.early-morning-fog-desc: Fog developed this autumn's morning. Expect good visibility above the layer. However - getting through it can be a challenge. Stay alive for a 500' climb and you'll see the sun!

scenario.name: ICE3 train demo (Frankfurt to Essen)
scenario.description:
This scenario runs an ICE3 train from Frankfurt Hbf to Essen Hbf.
Notes:
1. Units are ft, lbs, deg. 2. Lead/Tow Angle Gain are dimensionless multiplication factors. 3. Lead/TowAngle Limit Deg are the max excursion either side of the target/hitch heading 4. Rudder Constant is rudder increase/decrease in degrees/sec. 5. Speed Constant is increase/decrease in kts/sec. 6. contact_x(1/2)_offset define the points at which ground elevation is measured for pitch and elevation calulations in ft from the origin. Negative is forward. z and y components are not (yet) available. When x = 0 no pitch calculations are performed 7. Pitch Coefficient is a dimensionless damping factor for pitch (0.1) 8. Elevation Coefficient is a dimensionless damping factor for elevation (0.25)
Vivian Meazza

scenario.name: KRHV aerotow demo
scenario.description:
This scenario has a J3 takeoff from runway 31L at KRHV for aerotowing You can change the aircraft type by substituting another model in the <model> tag, and you can also change the "flight plan" by changing the <flightplan> tag. Look in the subdirectory FlightPlans to find some that I've already defined, including some arrivals. Normally, when an AI aircraft gets to the end of its flight plan it deletes itself, however the <repeat>1</repeat> tag will cause the AI aircraft to start again indefinitely.
Maik Justus, based D. Culps demo

scenario.name: 737 takeoff from KSFO/28L (San Francisco)
scenario.description:
This scenario has a 737 takeoff from runway 28L at KSFO and fly the Porte Departure to the south. You can change the aircraft type by substituting another model in the <model> tag, and you can also change the "flight plan" by changing the <flightplan> tag. Look in the subdirectory FlightPlans to find some that I've already defined, including some arrivals. Normally, when an AI aircraft gets to the end of its flight plan it deletes itself, however the <repeat>1</repeat> tag will cause the AI aircraft to start again indefinitely.

scenario.name: Aerial refueling demo (KSFO)
scenario.description:
The following scenario puts an aerial tanker in orbit over KSFO at 3000 ft AGL. The tanker uses the 737 model, but you can use any model (a KC-135 model can be found at: http://home.comcast.net/~davidculp2/hangar/hangar.html). The center of the orbit is actually west of KSFO, and the eastern edge of the orbit passes over the airport. Note that AI aircraft do not react to wind, therefore your speed and bank angle will have to vary along the orbit since your "user" aircraft *does* react to the wind.
I recommend using the T-38 as your airplane for four reasons: (1) it has a radar screen which may be needed to find the tanker; (2) it has the speed to catch the tanker; (3) it uses a JSBSim FDM, which means it can onload fuel; (4) it has a green light added to the instrument panel, between the fuel gauges, which comes on when you are in the refueling envelope.
Right now the air refueling envelope is very loose, and I plan on tightening it up in the future. Currently no aerodynamic effects of refueling are modeled (i.e downwash, bow wave, vortices).
Dave Culp, davidculp2 at comcast.net
